 , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Llewelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Dolphyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Dolfin</i>, apparently from an Anglo-Scandinavian formation, <i>Dólgfinnr</i> (possibly from Old Norse <i>dolgr</i>, <i>dólgr</i> ‘mortal enemy’ + the ethnic name <i>Finnr</i>), but there is disagreement about whether or not this might be a Scandinavianized form of Old French <i>Delfin</i> (from Latin <i>Delphinus</i>, from the word meaning ‘dolphin’). The surname was taken to Ireland at the time of the Anglo-Norman invasion in the 12th century, and the original bearers of the name settled in County Galway. The family became bilingual and the name has sometimes been Gaelicized as <b>Doilfin</b>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dolphyn ap Llewelyn Eurdorchog was born about 1040, in Dyffryn, Montgomeryshire, Wales, his father, Llewelyn Aurdorchog \"Golden-Torqued\" ap Coel, was 37 and his mother, Efa ferch Cynfyn, was 23. He married Mrs. Dolphyn ap Llewelyn in 0998, in Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1040–":"umbes 1040–Surnud","1035–Male":"1035–Surnud","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1036–Male":"1036–Surnud","1038–Male":"1038–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1076–1126":"1076–1126","0980–Female":"0980–Surnud","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1005–1065":"1005–1065","1018–Female":"1018–Surnud","about 1060":"umbes 1060","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1065":"1065","1076":"1076","1040":"1040","1060":"1060","1018":"1018","1005":"1005","0995":"0995","1126":"1126","1038":"1038","1036":"1036","1035":"1035","0980":"0980","of,,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Dyffryn, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Dyffryn, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1040–":"noin 1040–Kuollut","1035–Male":"1035–Kuollut","1035–Female":"1035–Kuollut","1036–Male":"1036–Kuollut","1038–Male":"1038–Kuollut","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1076–1126":"1076–1126","0980–Female":"0980–Kuollut","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1005–1065":"1005–1065","1018–Female":"1018–Kuollut","about 1060":"noin 1060","about 1040":"noin 1040","1065":"1065","1076":"1076","1040":"1040","1060":"1060","1018":"1018","1005":"1005","0995":"0995","1126":"1126","1038":"1038","1036":"10